docs.abstract: An Alan Turing manuscript sells for $1 million as interest in artifacts grows.
docs.snippet: An Alan Turing manuscript sells for $1 million as interest in artifacts grows.
docs.lead_paragraph: LONDON — The digital world is increasingly meshing with the art world. More and more art is being marketed and sold online. At the same time, relics from the early days of computing are drawing eye-catching prices, and more and more commercial galleries are showing works by innovative, Internet-savvy artists.

headline.main: Auctioning the Relics of Technology Pioneers
headline.print_headline: Auctioning the Relics of Technology Pioneers

docs.abstract: Maybe we actually want our mobile devices to be less addictive.
docs.snippet: Maybe we actually want our mobile devices to be less addictive.
docs.lead_paragraph: The Apple Watch promises to make users’ lives better in a number of ways, from helping them stay on schedule to tracking their physical activity. But early reviews of the product suggest another possible improvement: It might get us to quit staring at our phones.

headline.main: Will the Apple Watch Make Us Happier?

docs.abstract: Apps will allow users to peek at their balance and recent activity, but not to pay bills or make deposits.
docs.snippet: Apps will allow users to peek at their balance and recent activity, but not to pay bills or make deposits.

headline.main: Banking on Apple Watch Will Be Limited, for Now
headline.print_headline: Doing Banking on Apple Watch Will Be Limited, for Now

docs.abstract: Political polarization is making economic stagnation worse.
docs.snippet: Political polarization is making economic stagnation worse.
docs.lead_paragraph: Over the past three decades, the American economy has become less vigorous. An extensive body of evidence shows that the public focus on the success of high-tech companies like Apple and Google masks an overall downward trend in key measures of business vitality.

headline.main: Has American Business Lost Its Mojo?

docs.abstract: Apple’s retail head, Angela Ahrendts, has told retail employees that the Apple Watch will not be available for in-store purchasing on the day of its April 24 release.
docs.snippet: Apple’s retail head, Angela Ahrendts, has told retail employees that the Apple Watch will not be available for in-store purchasing on the day of its April 24 release.
docs.lead_paragraph: Apple’s method of releasing products like the iPhone is straightforward: On the day of release, you buy the phone at a retail store or it is delivered if you ordered online. The process is a lot less clear for the Apple Watch.

docs.abstract: The Apple Watch will be sold in just nine countries and only through its own channels, entering the world in a different manner from that of the iPhone.
docs.snippet: The Apple Watch will be sold in just nine countries and only through its own channels, entering the world in a different manner from that of the iPhone.
docs.lead_paragraph: SAN FRANCISCO — Apple has scrapped its usual routine for releasing products with its new device, the Apple Watch. The company is instead taking a page from the playbook of another industry: luxury goods makers.

headline.main: Changing Tactics, Apple Promotes Watch as a Luxury Item
headline.print_headline: Changing Strategy, Apple Promotes Its New Watch as a Luxury Item

docs.abstract: The politics behind the European Union’s antitrust charges against the American Internet giant.
docs.snippet: The politics behind the European Union’s antitrust charges against the American Internet giant.
docs.lead_paragraph: Have you heard the term Gafa yet? It hasn’t caught on here in the United States — and I’m guessing it won’t — but in France, it has become so common that the newspapers hardly need to spell out its meaning. Everyone there already knows what Gafa stands for: Google-Apple-Facebook-Amazon.
